Our theology and our science have benefited in proportion as this process has been ably carried out, by men of competent power, of fair and independent judgment, and, at the same time, adequately imbued with the learning and the mind of antiquity.

To say no more than this of a literature so vast in extent, and so powerful in its influence upon the present and the future interests of mankind, is indeed to say the least that can with decency be said of it. But for the present it may suffice.
